{"parse":{"title":"Isoazimuth","pageid":48429332,"revid":829606951,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>isoazimuth</b> is the <a href=\"/wiki/Locus_(mathematics)\" title=\"Locus (mathematics)\">locus</a> of the points on the Earth's surface whose initial <a href=\"/wiki/Great-circle_distance\" title=\"Great-circle distance\">orthodromic course</a> with respect to a fixed point is constant.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>That is, if the initial <a href=\"/wiki/Great-circle_distance\" title=\"Great-circle distance\">orthodromic course</a> Z from the starting point <i>S</i> to the fixed point <i>X</i> is 80  <a href=\"/wiki/Degree_(angle)\" title=\"Degree (angle)\">degrees</a>, the associated isoazimuth is formed by all points whose initial <a href=\"/wiki/Great-circle_distance\" title=\"Great-circle distance\">orthodromic course</a> with respect to point <i>X</i> is 80\u00b0 (with respect to true north). The isoazimuth is written using the notation <i>isoz(X, Z)</i>.\n</p><p>The isoazimuth is of use when <a href=\"/wiki/Navigation\" title=\"Navigation\">navigating</a> with respect to an object of known location, such as a radio beacon. A straight line called the <i>azimuth line of position</i> is drawn on a map, and on most common map projections this is a close enough approximation to the isoazimuth. On the <a href=\"/wiki/Littrow_projection\" title=\"Littrow projection\">Littrow projection</a>, the correspondence is exact. This line is then crossed with an astronomical observation called a <a href=\"/wiki/Sumner_line\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sumner line\">Sumner line</a>, and the result gives an estimate of the navigator's position.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Isoazimutal_on_the_spherical_Earth\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Isoazimutal on the spherical Earth</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Isoazimutal_of_a_star\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Isoazimutal of a star</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Isoazimutal_on_the_spherical_Earth\">Isoazimutal on the spherical Earth</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Isoazimuth&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Isoazimutal on the spherical Earth\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Let <b>X</b> be a fixed point on the Earth of coordinates latitude: <b>B2</b>, and longitude: <b>L2</b>. In a terrestrial spherical model, the equation of isoazimuth line of initial course <b>C</b> passing through point S(<b>B</b>, <b>L</b>) is:\n<b><span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle tan(B2)*cos(B)=sin(B)*cos(L2-L)+sin(L2-L)/tan(C)\\;}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>t</mi>\n        <mi>a</mi>\n        <mi>n</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>B</mi>\n        <mn>2</mn>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mo>&#x2217;<!-- \u2217 --></mo>\n        <mi>c</mi>\n        <mi>o</mi>\n        <mi>s</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>B</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mo>=</mo>\n        <mi>s</mi>\n        <mi>i</mi>\n        <mi>n</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>B</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mo>&#x2217;<!-- \u2217 --></mo>\n        <mi>c</mi>\n        <mi>o</mi>\n        <mi>s</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>L</mi>\n        <mn>2</mn>\n        <mo>&#x2212;<!-- \u2212 --></mo>\n        <mi>L</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mo>+</mo>\n        <mi>s</mi>\n        <mi>i</mi>\n        <mi>n</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>L</mi>\n        <mn>2</mn>\n        <mo>&#x2212;<!-- \u2212 --></mo>\n        <mi>L</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mo>/</mo>\n        </mrow>\n        <mi>t</mi>\n        <mi>a</mi>\n        <mi>n</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>C</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mspace width=\"thickmathspace\" />\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle tan(B2)*cos(B)=sin(B)*cos(L2-L)+sin(L2-L)/tan(C)\\;}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/5592e236742432f40084e88c9db77ec9c75e51e1\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:65.503ex; height:2.843ex;\" alt=\"{\\displaystyle tan(B2)*cos(B)=sin(B)*cos(L2-L)+sin(L2-L)/tan(C)\\;}\"/></span></b>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Isoazimutal_of_a_star\">Isoazimutal of a star</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Isoazimuth&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Isoazimutal of a star\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In this case the <b>X</b> point is the illuminating pole of the observed star, and the angle <b>Z</b> is its <a href=\"/wiki/Azimuth\" title=\"Azimuth\">azimuth</a>. The equation of the <i>isoazimuthal</i> <sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>curve for a star with coordinates (<b>Dec, Gha</b>), -<i>Declination</i> and <i>Greenwich Hour Angle</i>-, observed under an azimuth <b>Z</b> is given by:\n</p>\n<dl><dd><b><span class=\"mwe-math-element\"><span class=\"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y\" style=\"display: none;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"  alttext=\"{\\displaystyle \\cot(Z)/\\cos(B)=\\tan(Dec)/\\sin(lha)-\\tan(B)/\\tan(lha)\\;}\">\n  <semantics>\n    <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n      <mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\">\n        <mi>cot</mi>\n        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>Z</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mo>/</mo>\n        </mrow>\n        <mi>cos</mi>\n        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>B</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mo>=</mo>\n        <mi>tan</mi>\n        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>D</mi>\n        <mi>e</mi>\n        <mi>c</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mo>/</mo>\n        </mrow>\n        <mi>sin</mi>\n        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>l</mi>\n        <mi>h</mi>\n        <mi>a</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mo>&#x2212;<!-- \u2212 --></mo>\n        <mi>tan</mi>\n        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>B</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mrow class=\"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD\">\n          <mo>/</mo>\n        </mrow>\n        <mi>tan</mi>\n        <mo>&#x2061;<!-- \u2061 --></mo>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n        <mi>l</mi>\n        <mi>h</mi>\n        <mi>a</mi>\n        <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n        <mspace width=\"thickmathspace\" />\n      </mstyle>\n    </mrow>\n    <annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">{\\displaystyle \\cot(Z)/\\cos(B)=\\tan(Dec)/\\sin(lha)-\\tan(B)/\\tan(lha)\\;}</annotation>\n  </semantics>\n</math></span><img src=\"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/687bbde3e232ff0f249ef6dd5e150c0f46d78102\" class=\"mwe-math-fallback-image-inline\" aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:56.981ex; height:2.843ex;\" alt=\"{\\displaystyle \\cot(Z)/\\cos(B)=\\tan(Dec)/\\sin(lha)-\\tan(B)/\\tan(lha)\\;}\"/></span></b></dd></dl>\n<p>where <b>lha</b> is the  local hour angle, and all points with <b>latitude</b> <b>B</b> and <b>longitude</b> <b>L</b>, they define the curve.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Isoazimuth&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Great_circle\" title=\"Great circle\">Great circle</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Rhumb_line\" title=\"Rhumb line\">Rhumb line</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Geography\" title=\"Geography\">Geography</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Cartography\" title=\"Cartography\">Mapping</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Navigational_Algorithms\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Navigational Algorithms\">Navigational Algorithms</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Isoazimuth&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Flexner, W. W.. 1943. \u201cAzimuth Line of Position\u201d. The American Mathematical Monthly 50 (8). Mathematical Association of America: 475\u201384. doi:10.2307/2304185. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.jstor.org/stable/2304185?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents\">Accessed 2016-01-24</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Le segment capable sph\u00e9rique. Navigation N\u00ba.116 Vol.XXIX, Institut fran\u00e7ais de navigation, octubre/1981.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Isoazimuth&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Navigational Algorithms <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://sites.google.com/site/navigationalalgorithms/\">http://sites.google.com/site/navigationalalgorithms/</a></li>\n<li>Institut fran\u00e7ais de navigation <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.ifnavigation.org/\">http://www.ifnavigation.org/</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1287\nCached time: 20180904180828\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.040 seconds\nReal